	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Ugene</b><br /><i>Quote: Originally Posted by <b>GhostofthePast</b><br />
<i>We've basically created a number of very poor countries, that don't have much of anything in the way of an economy all with a buttload of weapons, some of them nuclear. To me, that makes for one hell of an unstable environment.<br />
</i><br />
 <br />
Ghost, your above quote asserts that "we've created" the poor countries that exist in the former Soviet Union.  That assertion ignores the historical fact that communism did quite nicely in creating death and poverty well before Ronald Reagan took office.  So you have confused causality with proximity here.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I can see where my initial post here is confusing.  Let me try and elaborate.<br />
<br />
Certianly the Soviets did most of the damage.  However, it seems to me that our approach of beating the USSR through an arms race inflamed that particular situation rather than improved it.  Even beyond that, it seems that we did precious little to attempt to stabilize that region through economic development after the fact.<br />
<br />
I want to make myself clear here.  I am not in the camp of the rabid Reagan haters that were quoted at the start of this thread.  However, I do feel that Reagan was in many respects a very bad president.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
