	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>The only difference with capitalism is we have the illusion of having choices.<br />
<br />
I believe that we have the capability, production and resources to give every man, woman, and child on earth the ability to live like an upper-middle class north american, while working only 3 or 4 days a week. I believe that a "star trek" style of economic utopia is completely possible, on a technical level. It's getting people to work together to make it happen that's the impossibility. For now.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br />
In communism, there are virtually no choices. Almost everything is government run. With capitalism, we can choose to buy almost any given product from private company "A" that dumps tonnes of toxic waste into the ocean or from private company "B" that is ecologically friendly. Product "B" may not be as good a quality as "A", but that is a choice we have. "The illusion of having choices" is about as far off the mark as you can get.<br />
 <br />
As for your utopian society, it would <i>require</i> that nobody could live any better than upper-middle class. That isn't freedom, and it couldn't work anyway. It has been proven time and time and time again that if you remove someone's incentive to accomplish something, then he or she will not attempt to accomplish it. If everybody were given an upper-middle class lifestyle, not enough of them would work 3 or 4 days a week to sustain the economy. That's precisely why socialism <i>does not work.</i> The rest of the work bitches and complains about the lifestyle of the "average" American being so much better than what they've got. It's the way it is because people like Ronald Reagan fought to contain the tide of European Socialism that is now sweeping the country.</p>
	
	
	
