	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>Once again, you are assuming I'm in favor of Socialism, which I'm not.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No. What I am "assuming" is that you directly stated that <i>nobody</i> should ever live any better than what is currently considered to be "upper-middle class." Ergo, there is a very low upper limit to just how much you can reward someone for doing anything. Let's say I invent something that allows everybody in the world to go from working your hypothetical 3 days a week to 2 days a week. The best reward you can give me under your described system is to allow me to live the same lifestyle as everybody else, but without having to work at all ever again. If I'm intelligent enough to come up with something so revolutionary, what makes you think it's the only thing I'm capable of inventing? Where's my incentive to apply myself to tackling a different problem? Even if I did so, how would you reward me? You couldn't. Therefore, you are not rewarding any type of behavior. In fact, you are damaging societal growth by effectively preventing me from coming up with something else. True altruism does not generally exist in nature except for a few exceptional cases. You cannot base your entire economic structure on it.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Tevyn Eagleye<br />
51st Pathfinder of Solusek Ro<br />
Retired</div>
	
	
