	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Tevyn</b><br /><i>No. What I am "assuming" is that you directly stated that <i>nobody</i> should ever live any better than what is currently considered to be "upper-middle class." </i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Tevyn, nobody DOES live better than upper middle class even now.<br />
<br />
At a certain point, wealth ceases to be about lifestyle, and starts to be about accumulation.<br />
 <br />
Your lifestyle shouldn't be static. Hitting the top should require going above and beyond the "duties" of your job. Maintaining that lifestyle should require continually doing so. Also, not all rewards are monetary.<br />
<br />
You are assuming a simplistic system is what I had in mind. Heck, you're assuming I've got a complete economic model already in my head.<br />
<br />
The simple fact is, capitalism has been in use for 6000 years, and it's been proven to work, but at the cost of a lot of lives. It's fundamentally flawed...it promotes exploiting others for your own gain, to their loss.<br />
<br />
Socialism does NOT work. The ideals of it are great, but the economic production is too low for it to be maintainable. <br />
<br />
We can do better. We can evolve, we can make a better system.</p>
	
	
	
